{
  "summary": "The text recounts the history of Jerusalem, focusing on two significant events. First, it describes how Jerusalem was besieged and destroyed by Titus, the son of Roman Emperor Vespasian, in the 42nd year after Christ's passion, as a result of the actions of the Jews, in alignment with the prophecy that no stone would remain on another. Later, the city was rebuilt by Aelius Hadrian, the Roman Emperor, and was subsequently referred to as Aelia. This is referenced in the records of the Nicaea synod, where the bishop of Aelia is noted as worthy of honor.",
  "keywords": [
    "Emperor Hadrian"
  ]
